									<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
								
				<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=52822'>			
	
			<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/humanl.jpg" border=0 alt="">
		</a><br>

				<span class=text_smallest>
								Server: Solusek Ro<br>
								</span>

								
			
			
									<p>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
										Viewed 127 times<br>
									</span>

									
									</td>

						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#0C142B" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV></DIV><FONT size=2>
<P>My 2 cp. Here goes.</P>
<P><STRONG>The root of the problem</STRONG></P>
<P>I propose that the current bard spellcasting situation is fundamentally flawed, because the interface no longer applies to the original roleplaying and gameplay design. Bard twisting functionality has been left in, and has evolved with the bard class and songs - a bard is now judged based on having several song effects in play at once. Twisting doesn't need to be taken out of the game, but it needs to be properly implemented, something which wasn't thought of before the game was tested, and which still has not been addressed. It is perhaps the oldest gameplay deficiency in EQ.</P>
<P>Regarding not being able to use item effects while a song is being played, and proc's interrupting songs that are being played: these issues exist due to the original implementation of the 'bards singing one song at a time' idea. Since bards are effectively continuously casting a spell while a song is in effect, they cannot use these items properly. This is an unfair hinderance applied to the bard class for no other reason except that they had to code the bard spell system in such a way as to comply with the initial roleplaying idea. I think this is a side effect that was never intended to be so detrimental and should be fixed.</P>
<P><STRONG>Working towards a solution</STRONG></P>
<P>A beleive a new bard song paradigm is needed. It must be retrofitted into the current system, and therefore should incorporate the following:</P>
<UL>
<LI>singing/instrument skills</LI>
<LI>singing/instrument mods</LI>
<LI>missed notes</LI>
<LI>several bard song effects in use at once (at least 3-4)</LI>
<LI>keep&nbsp;manual twisting an option for those who&nbsp;want an extra challenge (optional)</LI>
<LI>keep the 8 spell gems for prepared songs</LI>
<LI>song effects and ranges stay the same</LI></UL>
<P><STRONG>The evolution of the bard class</STRONG></P>
<P><U>Initial idea:</U></P>
<P>Roleplaying: <EM>Bards use magic by singing songs that produce magical effects.&nbsp; Since the magic comes from the song, a bard can only have one of these effects in play at a given time, but they have a wide variety of different song effects they can switch between (i.e. stop singing one song, start singing another), to make themselves useful in many situations.</EM></P>
<P>Gameplay: Bards can memorize up to 8 songs, like other spellcasters memorize spells, but when one is activated, is is continuously being cast, to maintain the roleplaying concept of bards only being able to sing one song at a time.</P>
<P><U>Current reality:</U></P>
<P>Roleplaying: <EM>Bards use magic by singing songs that produce magical effects.&nbsp; Bards can somehow sing multiple songs at once. Gnomes have started to become curious about their multitasking abilities and are looking for volunteer test subjects.</EM></P>
<P>Gameplay: Bard spell effects last for several server ticks, therefore a bard can, by clicking on and off their spell gems, "twist" up to four or more song effects together at one time.</P>
<P><U>An idea proposal (thanks to Ivoire and others for&nbsp;idea):</U></P>
<P>Roleplaying: <EM>Unlike other arcane spellcasters in Norrath, who recite an incantation and use gestures and components to summon forth magical energies from the world, a bard does so by singing a song that is magically empowered to create an effect. The bard's magical music, when used to benefit his teammates, can only affect those close enough to hear the notes. The magical effects the bard creates through song continue to function so long as he maintains a basic melody that carries between the different verses. Bards are masters of this kind of arcane music, and are commonly known to interweave several epic verses to create unique inspiration for their fellow adventurers.</EM></P>
<P>Gameplay: A bard's song gems and spell durations work differently from other spellcasters. Songs still have a casting time, but once a song is started, it will keep playing indefinitely, unless the song gem is clicked again or a missed note occurs, or the song is otherwise interrupted. The effects of up to four songs can be in play at once. While the bard has four song effects in play, one of the other songs in the lineup cannot be activated unless one of the first four is turned off. So for example, a bard could have three group beneficial song effects in play, and keep a fourth song effect available to use with one of his five other prepared songs, when the proper situation arises. For targeted songs, once the song begins playing it will continue to affect the original target until the song effect stops or the target disappears. Missed notes are checked for on all the song effects that the bard has in play. When a missed note occurs, that song effect will not be refreshed and the song gem will unselect and will need to be cast again.</P>
<P>This is just one suggestion for a better way to do this. I hope there are many more.</P>
<P><STRONG>Final thoughts</STRONG></P>
<P>I think the twisting problem lies at the beginning of EQ. It reaches all the way back to initial development questions and ideas. Assuming that SOE officialy condones multiple song effects (twisting), I think we should hash out a solid solution that will make the most sense to all EQ players, both current and future. SOE's belief is that the friends people make in EQ is what keeps them coming back, so I doubt they are completely satisfied with&nbsp;a character class that doesn't let people chat. At this point, the ideas for solving this problem will probably come from the EQ community.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>p.s. I really like the "/useitem&nbsp;slot_number" idea</P></FONT>
																		
										</td></tr>
